  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset titled \"ORCID in Book Workflows: Survey\" is a foundational research output available on Figshare. Although it has yet to garner notable citations or community mentions, it presents an opportunity for future research into the integration of ORCID identifiers in book publishing workflows.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset \"ORCID in Book Workflows: Survey,\" authored by terence smyre and Alice Meadows among others, represents an essential contribution to understanding how ORCID identifiers can be effectively utilized within book publishing processes. Hosted on Figshare, this dataset is positioned to advance scholarly communications by providing empirical data on a significant aspect of academic publishing.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the current lack of academic citations or community discourse surrounding this dataset, its availability as a dataset on Figshare provides a valuable resource for researchers interested in exploring the role of ORCID in enhancing the discoverability and attribution of scholarly works. Its designation as a dataset emphasizes the authors' commitment to open data practices, which facilitate transparency and further research opportunities.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset has been accessed four times, indicating a modest engagement and hinting at its potential relevance. This initial level of interest could serve as a precursor for deeper academic inquiry and analysis over time, suggesting that researchers may be beginning to recognize the importance of ORCID integration in the academic book landscape.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">As this dataset remains available for exploration, it invites future investigations and applications. Researchers and practitioners are encouraged to utilize this data as a foundation for studies that can further inform and enhance book publishing workflows, ultimately contributing to the ongoing evolution of academic attribution standards.</p>",
